// LA-30 doc 5 §4 "nested_spawn_join.lev" — a worker inside a worker; joins
// rethrow correctly at each level. `outer` spawns `middle`, which itself
// spawns `inner` and awaits it locally (same thread that created it) before
// returning — no bare Promise crosses a thread it wasn't created on, so this
// never trips A-1's spawn-body-Promise reject (bug #35, reject route A: a spawn
// body referencing a Promise through a capture OR a bare global is rejected —
// see spawn_global_promise_rejected.lev). Verified byte-identical on
// oracle/IR/LLVM.
//
// `inner`'s throw rejects its Worker; `middle`'s `await w` rethrows it (a
// catchable RuntimeException, doc 2 §7's existing spawn try/catch, no new
// plumbing); `outer`'s body is `middle()` itself, so the same exception
// propagates out of `outer`'s body, rejecting `outer`'s Worker in turn;
// the top-level `await outer` rethrows it once more, caught here.
int inner() {
    throw RuntimeException("inner boom");
    return 0;                       // unreachable, satisfies the int return type
}
int middle() {
    Worker<int> w = std::spawn(() => inner());
    return await w;
}
Worker<int> outer = std::spawn(() => middle());
try { console.writeln(await outer); }
catch (RuntimeException e) { console.writeln(e.message); }   // inner boom
